![](http://ootput.files.wordpress.com/2012/06/logo_gist.png?w=150 "logo_gist")

While `WordPress.com` doesn’t allow you to use potentially harmful code on your blog, it does allow you to post source code for general viewing. Provided that you enclose the source code within a `&#091;sourcecode&#093; &#091;/sourcecode&#093;` [`shortcode`](http://en.support.rdpress.com/shortcodes/) wrapper, you will be able to preserve the code's formatting; enable syntax highlighting for the programming language used; and highlight specific lines in the code. For example, for a CSS snippet, do:
<!--more-->

{% codeblock lang:css %}
&#091;sourcecode language=&quot;css&quot; highlight=&quot;3,4,5,6,7&quot;&#093;

/* HTML5 display-role reset for older browsers */
article, aside, details, figcaption, figure,
footer, header, hgroup, menu, nav, section {
	display: block;
}
body {
	line-height: 1;
}
ol, ul {
	list-style: none;
}
blockquote, q {
	quotes: none;
}
blockquote:before, blockquote:after,
q:before, q:after {
	content: '';
	content: none;
}
table {
	border-collapse: collapse;
	border-spacing: 0;
}

&#091;&#047;sourcecode&#093;
{% endcodeblock %}


Alternatively, `wordpress.com` permits embedding `github.com` gists by using the `&#091;gist&#093;` shortcode. With `&#091;gist&#093;2927943&#091;/gist&#093;`, you'll achieve:
[gist]2927943[/gist]

... which certainly isn't as pretty as `wordpress.com`'s solution. You can make a gist more presentable by way of CSS customizations, but this isn't possible on `wordpress.com`. It is also impossible to tell gists to highlight specific lines of code.
